                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="319926" author="adilger" created="Thu, 2 Dec 2021 21:24:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;While it would be possible to warn on a bad commit ID, I don&apos;t think it is possible to make this an error, because backporting patches with these commit messages to repositories that don&apos;t have the original commit should not fail.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="104005" author="morrone" created="Tue, 20 Jan 2015 16:39:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Here are a couple:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;5748379d28846c672f793ba1f8e143e63531dd05

e5966bdbb7c7644cc04580ad6b4a9006def3f758
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="103816" author="adilger" created="Sat, 17 Jan 2015 07:01:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Chris, this seems reasonable, and should be doable by the script. Do you have specific examples where the commit hash was bad?  Presumably they are all on b2_5?  In some cases I guess there are commit hashes from the upstream kernel in commit messages going to master, but they should be marked with &lt;tt&gt;Linux-commit:&lt;/tt&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
